cs.IT, cs.CR, cs.NI, cs.SY, cs.MM 

The paper discusses fundamental properties of full-duplex radio for secure wireless communication, which involves information theory (cs.IT), cryptography (cs.CR), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), systems and control (cs.SY), and multimedia (cs.MM). The paper specifically focuses on the secrecy capacity of a wireless channel, which is a key concept in information theory and cryptography. Therefore, cs.IT and cs.CR are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the impact of self-interference cancelation/suppression on the secrecy capacity, which is related to systems and control (cs.SY). Additionally, the paper considers the case of colluding and non-colluding eavesdroppers, which is relevant to networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). Finally, the paper may have implications for multimedia applications of wireless communication (cs.MM).
